node.text:
Starting January 1, 2022, France will be offering free contraception to all women under 25. The upcoming policy change was announced by Health Minister Olivier Véran on France-2 television.⁠
⁠
Starting in 2013, France made contraception free for people aged 15 to 18 and followed by extending it to those under 15 in August 2020. The number of abortions in France dropped following the policies’ implementation, per The Guardian. Abortions in France are free for all women and girls.⁠
⁠
‘This will cover hormonal contraception, biological tests that go with it, the prescription of contraception and all care related to this contraception up until the age of 25,’ Minister Véran told France-2. ‘There is a decline in the use of contraception among a certain number of young women, and the main reason for this is financial. It costs too much. It is unacceptable that women cannot protect themselves, cannot have contraception if that’s their choice obviously, because they cannot afford it.’⁠
⁠
The cut-off age is 25, according to Minister Véran, because it coincides with the age that people are more autonomous and are no longer covered by their parent’s health insurance, per The Guardian.⁠
⁠
#contraception #france #abortions

node.text:
The LAPD has reportedly instructed its officers to collect social media information on every civilian they stop, even if they haven't been arrested or accused of a crime, according to documents obtained by the Brennan Center for Justice.

BCJ claims to have reviewed 10 sets of documents obtained through a request to the LAPD under the California Public Records Act, which it says reveal the department's diverse mass surveillance tactics, including collecting social media information during interviews. The nonprofit organization says the procedure raises concerns about the department infringing on the civil liberties of civilians without a warrant.

According to the Guardian, with whom BCJ shared the documents, LAPD officers utilize 'field interview cards,' which include space for them to record social media account information on any civilian they speak to. According to the Guardian, police chief Michel Moore allegedly told officers and their supervisors that it ‘was critical to collect the data for use in ‘investigations, arrests, and prosecutions,’ and warned that supervisors would review cards to ensure they were complete.’

'There are real dangers about police having all of this social media identifying information at their fingertips,' said Rachel Levinson-Waldman, a deputy director at BCJ, to the Guardian.

'There is a long history of law enforcement using surveillance, whether in-person or through digital technologies to attack Black and Latino movements fighting for racial justice,' added Jacinta González, an organizer with advocacy group Mijente.

#losangeles #lapd #socialmedia #justice
